"# Chapter 6 — Cables and connectors

A cable is a wire in a jacket. A connector is what makes the
cable easy to plug into a thing. A lot of engineering hides in
the boring reliability of connectors that click. Motoi wants
you to know why some cables and connectors are more expensive
than others.

## The cheap cable myth

A cable is not just wire. It is:

- Copper conductors (or aluminum, for cheap ones — this is a
  yellow flag for anything carrying real current).
- Insulation around each conductor (PVC, PTFE, silicone —
  different materials for different heat and flex needs).
- A shield in some cables — a woven or foil layer that keeps
  external noise out and internal signal in.
- A jacket around the whole thing.
- Strain relief at the connector ends so pulling on the cable
  doesn't rip the wire out of the plug.

You get what you pay for. A $2 USB cable and a $30 USB cable
often move the same bytes. They differ in longevity, flex
tolerance, resistance to noise, and how badly they fail as they
wear.

## Common connectors and what they cost you

- **USB-A** — the rectangular one. Ubiquitous, robust, and only
  goes in one way (though it never feels like it).
- **USB-C** — reversible, small, carries huge power and data.
  Won a war. Now the standard.
- **HDMI** — carries digital video plus audio. The clicking
  latch is small; the cable is heavy; the plug wobbles easily.
- **RJ45** — the ethernet one. The little plastic tab that
  clicks is the reason your network stays up. Break the tab,
  buy a new cable.
- **BNC** — twist-lock. Common on oscilloscope probes and RF
  gear. Impedance-matched — see below.
- **XLR** — three-pin, used for balanced audio (microphones).
  Big satisfying click. Locks.
- **JST, Molex, Dupont** — small board-to-board connectors. If
  you build hobby electronics, you meet these fast.
- **Barrel jack** — the round DC power connector. Center-
  positive or center-negative — always check before plugging
  in.

## Impedance — the part beginners don't hear about

At low frequencies, a wire is just a wire. Voltage in one end
comes out the other. At high frequencies, wires start
behaving like transmission lines: they have a characteristic
impedance measured in ohms, and if the impedance of the cable
doesn't match the impedance of the source and load, energy
reflects back down the cable.

Reflections cause distortion, ringing, and lost data.

Common impedances:

- **50 ohms** — RF cabling, oscilloscope probes, most test gear.
  BNC connectors on lab equipment are 50Ω by default.
- **75 ohms** — TV and cable, video, some audio. RCA video
  cables are 75Ω.
- **100 ohms** — differential pairs in USB and ethernet.
- **~120 ohms** — CAN bus (car networking).

For a cable to work at high frequency, the geometry of the
conductor and shield has to hold the target impedance. This is
why RF cable is expensive. It is not just wire in a jacket. It
is precisely-controlled geometry.

For low-frequency signals (audio, DC power, slow serial), you
can ignore impedance. For anything above about 10 MHz, you
cannot.

## The click

When you plug something in and hear a small click, that's
usually a latch. Latches keep the connector from falling out.
A good latch is a small engineering triumph.

The reason USB-A doesn't click is that it's a friction fit.
The reason ethernet does click is the plastic tab. The reason
XLR does is the spring-loaded pin. The reason HDMI often
doesn't stay in is that its latch is small and the cable is
heavy — a known bad shape.

If a connector doesn't latch and it needs to, that connection
will fail when someone bumps the desk. Design your bench so
important connections have latching plugs whenever possible.

## Contact resistance

Every plug has a small resistance where the two metal surfaces
touch. If the metals are clean and the spring pressure is
right, this resistance is a few milliohms. If the contacts are
tarnished, oily, or the spring has weakened with age, the
resistance climbs.

Symptoms of bad contact:

- Intermittent — works when you wiggle the plug.
- Voltage drop across the connector under load.
- Heat at the connector.
- Poor high-frequency performance.

Fix: unplug, clean the contacts, replug. Contact cleaner spray
works. Alcohol on a swab works for light tarnish. For
irreversible corrosion, replace the cable.

## What Motoi can and cannot do here

Motoi cannot check your cable. Motoi cannot see the connector
you're holding. But Motoi knows the shapes and can talk about
them.

If your USB device isn't recognized, he might ask: is it
plugged in fully? Is the cable a data cable or a charge-only
cable (some cheap USB cables have no data lines wired)? Have
you tried a different port?

The disposition: 'I can talk about cables. I can't see yours.
Describe what's happening and I'll try to help you rule things
out.'

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Cables and connectors are boring on purpose. The good ones are
reliable, click satisfyingly, and don't fail when the desk
gets bumped. The bad ones fail intermittently, which is worse
than failing all the way.

If you're building something you care about, spend real money
on the cables. It's the cheapest and least-thanked reliability
investment you can make.")
